{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem *Ek Makra aur Makhi* (\"A Spider and a Fly\") from *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, the spider begins luring the fly with a polite invitation to enter his web, disguised as a humble hut.[^1]\n\n> A spider to a fly one day did say,  \n> “You travel daily down this very way,  \n>   \n> But my poor hut has never been so blessed,  \n> That you might stop and be my honored guest.  \n>   \n> To shun a stranger is no great disgrace,  \n> But from your own, don't keep such distant space.  \n>   \n> If you would come, my honor would increase,  \n> The winding stair is there, if you should please.”[^1]\n\nAfter the fly's initial refusal, the spider reflects that **flattery** is the key to success (\"But flattery can make a hundred schemes succeed, / The world is slave to flattery's own creed\") and then lavishes praise on her beauty to draw her in.[^2][^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 20 \"Ek Makra aur Makhi\" (translation), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/20-ek-makra-aur-makhi/translation/#p-02078b).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 20 \"Ek Makra aur Makhi\" (translation), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/20-ek-makra-aur-makhi/translation/#p-1409dc).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 20 \"Ek Makra aur Makhi\" (translation), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/20-ek-makra-aur-makhi/translation/#p-d0b552).",
